Conclusion

This query demonstrates how to retrieve payroll deduction results from Oracle Fusion Payroll using:

Payroll run results
Payroll processing actions
Element result values
Date-effective employee records

It can serve as a reusable foundation for payroll integrations, benefit exports, and reconciliation reporting solutions.

What I Learned

The Oracle Fusion Payroll results chain (ppa → ppra → prr → prrv) must be traversed in full — there is no shortcut table that flattens run results for reporting
PAY_ELEMENT_ENTRIES_F stores what an employee is enrolled for; PAY_RUN_RESULT_VALUES stores what was actually calculated and processed — these can differ and should never be confused
The cut_off_date IS NOT NULL filter on PAY_TIME_PERIODS is a critical guard against pulling in-progress payroll data — missing it is a common bug in Fusion Payroll reports
BCB element prefixes in Fusion Benefits indicate Benefits Calculation Base elements — understanding the naming convention helps quickly identify element purpose and behavior
For third-party benefits files, it is cleaner to apply the FSA/DCA code mapping in SQL (CASE expression) rather than in the RTF template — it keeps business logic in one versioned, testable place
